JOHANNESBURG - South African consumer confidence remained depressed in the last three months of 2017. The FNB sponsored research, conducted by the Bureau for Economic Research, showed consumer sentiment improved but remained in the negative. READ: Rise of consumer confidence It went from negative five to negative eight points, remaining below the zero mark. This was the third straight year of pessimism from consumers, the longest streak in over three years. Analysts say despite softening inflation, actual price levels for basic necessities remained high, which further wore out purchasing power, especially for lower income households. The outlook for government finances was cited as one of the greatest risks to consumer spending in 2018. The research was concluded before the African National Congress (ANC)â€™s elective conference, which took place in Johannesburg over December and saw Cyril Ramaphosa narrowly take the party's top job. eNCA